<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B79164878E8FB4C279BFA29" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B79164878E8FB4C279BFA29" blockId="9.[136,1452,1022,1841]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B79164878E8FB4C26D7FB01" bold="true" box="[189,397,1166,1192]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B79164879FCFB4C25D3FB01" authorityName="Krapovickas &amp; Bueno" authorityYear="2014" box="[425,649,1166,1192]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="farroupilhensis">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B79164879FCFB4C25D3FB01" box="[425,649,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Sida farroupilhensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distincted from other species of section 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B7916487C02FB4C23CFFB01" box="[1111,1173,1166,1192]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Sidae">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7916487C02FB4C23CFFB01" box="[1111,1173,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Sidae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation id="4A6403360B7916487CF4FB4C23A8FB01" box="[1185,1266,1166,1192]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,340,364]" captionTargetBox="[144,1440,425,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sections of Sida with species occurring in Rio Grande do Sul state, and their diagnostic features, according to Fryxell (1985) and Krapovickas (2003)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" tableUuid="539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39">Table 1</tableCitation>
) by the presence of aristae smaller than the mericarp body, mericarps dehiscent only at the apex, solitary flowers without bifid bracts, leaf blades ovate-rhombic and with simple trichomes in adaxial surface (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B7916487B95FB142305FB59" box="[960,1119,1238,1264]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[248,1340,353,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-118@10.[248,1340,353,1895]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. A–F. Sida farroupilhensis. A. Flower. B. Abaxial surface of leaf. C. Adaxial surface of leaf. D. Mature schizocarp. E. Mature and immature schizocarps. F. Branch with leaves and flowers buds. G–J Sida linifolia. G. Abaxial surface of leaf. H. Buds in terminal umbelliform inflorescence. I. Schizocarps and buds in terminal umbelliform inflorescence J. Branch with flowers and buds. K–Q. Sida lonchitis. K. Flowers. L, N. Adaxial surface of leaf. M. Abaxial surface of leaf. O. Terminal inflorescence. P. Bifid bracts (black arrow). Q. Schizocarps. Photographs I–J by Luís Funez, all others by Martin Grings (G–J from N.I. Matzenbacher, ICN 123026)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415495/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Figures 4A–F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B7916487C3EFB1423C1FB59" box="[1131,1179,1238,1264]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-54@26.[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 14. Mericarps. A. Sida anomala. B. Sida confusa. C. Sida farroupilhensis. D. Sida glaziovii. E. Sida cerradoensis. F. Sida cordifolia. G. Sida dubia. H. Sida linifolia. I. Sida lonchitis. J. Sida nemorensis. K. Sida paradoxa. L. Sida planicaulis. M. Sida potentilloides.N. Sida reitzii. O. Sida regnellii. P. Sida rhombifolia.Q. Sida riedelii. R. Sida rubifolia.S. Sida spinosa.T. Sida tuberculata. U. Sida urens. V. Sida viarum. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415519/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">14C</figureCitation>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B7916487CE7FB1422DDFB59" author="Krapovickas, A." box="[1202,1415,1238,1264]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" pagination="65 - 118" refId="ref19583" refString="Krapovickas, A. (2014) Nuevas especies de Sida Seccion Sida (Malvaceae). Bonplandia 23: 65 - 118. https: // doi. org / 10.30972 / bon. 232258" type="journal article" year="2014">Krapovickas 2014</bibRefCitation>
). A relevant diagnostic feature of the species is the reticulate leaf’s abaxial surface, formed by the tertiary veins, which is covered by sparse, small stellate trichomes. Calyx also with tertiary veins forming a characteristic reticulate and with very sparse small stellate trichomes. In the present work, photos of the species in its habitat are presented for the first time.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B79164878E8FA482676F9F1" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B79164878E8FA482676F9F1" blockId="9.[136,1452,1022,1841]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B79164878E8FA4825B4FA0D" bold="true" box="[189,750,1418,1444]" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Distribution, habitat, and conservation status:</emphasis>
—The species is endemic to Araucaria Forest of northeast of 
<collectingRegion id="C522F86F0B79164878DDFA6C2606FA61" box="[136,348,1454,1480]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B7916487932FA6C26F1FA61" box="[359,427,1454,1480]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B79164879EFFA6C2546FA61" box="[442,540,1454,1480]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1971,1993]" captionTargetBox="[262,1350,253,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[199,1389,190,1947]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution map of Sida anomala, S. cerradoensis, S. confusa, S. cordifolia, S. dubia, S. farroupilhensis and S. lonchitis in Rio Grande do Sul state, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415491/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">Figure 2</figureCitation>
), in the edges or understory of Forests, and rarely in Highland grassland. With an EOO of 3,813.842 Km² and an AOO of 
<quantity id="C01E9B680B7916487A00FA1025C7FA46" box="[597,669,1490,1519]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" unit="km" value="40.0">40 km</quantity>
² 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B7916487AFBFA11242FFA45" authorityName="Krapovickas &amp; Bueno" authorityYear="2014" box="[686,885,1490,1517]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="9" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="farroupilhensis">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7916487AFBFA11242FFA45" box="[686,885,1490,1517]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="114">S. farroupilhensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be considered Endangered (EN). However, the species is usually abundant in places where it occurs and does not show subpopulations, locations, EOO and AOO declines or fluctuations. That is, the species does not meet the conditions B (a), B(b) and B(c) and is considered Least Concern (LC).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
